%[text] %[text:anchor:T_76D33CB4] # Power Converter Circuit and Control Design with Simscape
%[text] Power converters are basic building blocks for different electrification applications such as motor drives, chargers, automobiles, aerospace, distributed generation, renewable, battery energy storage systems, and consumer appliances.
%[text] This repository helps you design and simulate modern power converters and control algorithms. This repository contains two design solutions. One focuses on the grid-forming converter and the other on the LLC converter.
%[text:tableOfContents]{"heading":"Table of Contents"}
%[text] **Key words:** Power Converter, Grid-Forming Converters, Virtual Synchronous Machine, Droop Control, Virtual Impedance, Fault Ride Through, LLC Converter, 2P2Z compensator, Resonant converter
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_4af3] ## Design and Analysis of Grid-Forming Converter
%[text] The shift from synchronous machines to power electronics-based converters has introduced challenges like reduced system inertia and limited short-circuit current capacity. Traditional grid-following (GFM) converter control, which depends on grid measurements and PLL, can not fully address these issues. GFM converters provide a better solution by emulating the inertia, damping, fault current, and power control capabilities of synchronous machines through control strategies that mimic their dynamic response.
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_C2DCF662] This figure shows a GFM converter connected to a typical network with renewable sources, a load, and a utility grid.
%[text] ![](text:image:1500)
%[text] The GFM design solution shows you how to develop and test a grid-forming (GFM) converter control. The design solution helps you to:
%[text] - Design a generic GFM converter and analyze its transient response.
%[text] - Implement an alternative inertia emulation technique to enhance stability.
%[text] - Configure control loops for flexible tuning and performance optimization.
%[text] - Apply different current-limiting methods for safe operation under fault conditions.
%[text] - Adapt the design to a wide range of network strengths.
%[text] - Verify conformance to grid codes \[[1](internal:M_EB223F76)\]. \
%[text] [Click here](matlab:openMainScript('GridFormingConverterMain')) to open the main live script for the grid-forming converter design solution.
%[text] ![](text:image:7058)
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_ED7FB925] ### Standard Test Scenarios for Grid-Forming Converters 
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_419D4B21] This GFM design solution studies the performance of a GFM converter in test scenarios from the grid code standard GC0137 \[[1](internal:M_EB223F76)\]. This figure shows the GFM converter test scenarios found in the grid code standard GC0137 \[[1](internal:M_EB223F76)\]. The standard requires stable operation during grid disturbances, including changes in system frequency, phase, and voltage.
%[text] ![](text:image:90ce)
%[text] ## Design of LLC Resonant Converter
%[text]  This design solution helps you design and analyze a full-bridge LLC resonant converter. The design solution helps you to:
%[text] - Develop an LLC converter that meets your specifications.
%[text] - Plot gain curves for various load conditions, quality factors, and inductor ratios.
%[text] - Fine-tune the converter by adjusting the quality factor and inductor ratio to achieve the required performance.
%[text] - Apply a time-domain simulation method to linearize the plant for control design.
%[text] - Design and tune the compensator in the controller to meet control performance requirements.
%[text] - Estimate power loss in each component of the converter and calculate the overall efficiency by using support functions. \
%[text] [Click here](matlab:openMainScript('LLCResonantConverterFullBridgeMain')) to open the main live script for the LLC converter design solution.
%[text] ![](text:image:613a)
%[text] 
%[text] ![](text:image:6e05)
